The psychedelic clinical trials landscape has never been more active or more promising. With major studies reading out in depression, PTSD, substance use disorders, and neurodegenerative diseases, 2026 is shaping up to be a pivotal year. Here are the trials to watch.

## The Trials That Could Change Everything

The last three years have seen an unprecedented surge in psychedelic research. Propelled by [regulatory milestones](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/psychedelic-therapy-australia-2026), [major investments](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/psyfinance), and a growing public appetite for new mental health solutions, the field is moving at a pace that would have been unimaginable a decade ago.

As of July 2026, there are over 100 active psychedelic clinical trials worldwide. But a handful stand out for their potential to fundamentally reshape how we treat mental health conditions.

**These are the heavyweights. The game-changers. The studies that could make psychedelic medicine a first-line treatment option for millions of people.**

And they are all reading out in the next 12 months.

## Psilocybin for Treatment-Resistant Depression

Leading the pack is PSILODEP-2, Monash University's phase 2 randomised controlled trial of psilocybin-assisted therapy for treatment-resistant depression.

With 160 participants across multiple sites, it is the largest psilocybin trial in the Southern Hemisphere. Its results could be transformative.

**Why it matters:** Treatment-resistant depression affects 100 million people worldwide. One-third of people with depression do not respond to existing medications. If psilocybin proves effective for even a fraction of these cases, it could represent one of the most significant advances in depression treatment in decades.

**What to watch:** The study completes in November 2026. Top-line results may follow in the first quarter of 2027.

## MDMA for PTSD

Next is MAPS-2, the confirmatory phase 3 trial of MDMA-assisted therapy for PTSD.

It builds on an earlier phase 3 study that found **67% of participants no longer qualified for a PTSD diagnosis after treatment involving three MDMA sessions**.

**Why it matters:** PTSD affects millions of people worldwide and can be difficult to treat. Current first-line options, including SSRIs and prolonged exposure therapy, do not work for everyone and can have high dropout rates.

If confirmatory research supports the earlier findings, MDMA-assisted therapy could become an important treatment option for people with severe PTSD.

**What to watch:** Enrolment is ongoing, with further data expected in late 2026 or early 2027.

## LSD for Alcohol Use Disorder

MindMed's phase 2b trial of LSD for alcohol use disorder is one of the most advanced modern psychedelic studies in addiction.

With 200 participants across seven sites, it is also one of the largest LSD studies conducted in more than 50 years.

**Why it matters:** Alcohol use disorder contributes to millions of deaths globally each year. Existing treatments such as naltrexone can help, but their effectiveness and adherence remain limited for many people.

If LSD-assisted treatment proves effective, it could introduce a different approach centred on psychological insight, behavioural change, and structured therapeutic support.

**What to watch:** The study is fully enrolled, with results expected in the fourth quarter of 2026.

## Psilocybin for Alzheimer's Disease

Perhaps the most intriguing study on the horizon is an upcoming phase 2 trial exploring psilocybin in people with Alzheimer's disease.

Preclinical research suggests that psychedelics may influence neuroplasticity, inflammation, and the growth of new neural connections. However, these findings do not yet prove that psilocybin can slow cognitive decline in humans.

This research may first help determine whether psilocybin can reduce depression, anxiety, and existential distress in people living with neurodegenerative disease.

**Why it matters:** Alzheimer's disease remains one of the greatest unmet medical challenges. Even modest improvements in quality of life, mood, or cognitive flexibility could be meaningful for patients and families.

**What to watch:** Enrolment is expected to begin in late 2026, with data likely to become available later.

## DMT and Short-Acting Psychedelic Treatments

DMT is attracting growing clinical interest because its acute effects can be much shorter than those of psilocybin or LSD.

A psilocybin-assisted therapy session can last six hours or longer. This requires specialised rooms, trained staff, and extensive clinical supervision.

A shorter-acting psychedelic could potentially make treatment easier and less expensive to deliver. Researchers are therefore studying DMT and related compounds for depression and other mental health conditions.

Key questions include:

- Whether short experiences can produce lasting therapeutic benefits
- How much psychological support patients need
- Whether shorter sessions improve accessibility
- How safety compares with longer-acting psychedelics
- Whether benefits remain after the initial treatment period

A shorter experience does not automatically mean a safer or more effective treatment. Clinical trials will need to establish whether DMT can offer meaningful benefits within a practical treatment model.

## Ketamine and Rapid-Acting Antidepressant Research

Ketamine is not a classic serotonergic psychedelic, but it remains central to psychedelic medicine because of its rapid antidepressant effects.

Unlike psilocybin and LSD, ketamine already has a long medical history as an anaesthetic. Ketamine clinics now operate in several countries, while esketamine has received regulatory approval for certain forms of treatment-resistant depression.

Researchers continue to investigate:

- The ideal number of ketamine sessions
- How long antidepressant effects last
- Whether psychotherapy improves outcomes
- Which patients are most likely to respond
- The risks of repeated or long-term use
- How ketamine compares with psilocybin-assisted therapy

Ketamine research may also help scientists understand how rapid changes in neuroplasticity influence depression.

## The Australian Advantage

Australia is uniquely positioned to contribute to this research renaissance.

With [progressive regulations](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/australia-psilocybin-approval-2026), a strong clinical trials infrastructure, and growing support for innovative mental health research, Australia has become an important hub for psychedelic medicine.

Since July 2023, authorised psychiatrists have been able to prescribe psilocybin for treatment-resistant depression and MDMA for PTSD under tightly controlled conditions.

This did not make psychedelic therapy broadly available. Treatment remains highly restricted, expensive, and limited to approved practitioners and eligible patients.

However, the regulatory shift has increased international interest in Australia's psychedelic sector. Universities, clinics, charities, and biotechnology companies are now involved in studies covering psilocybin, MDMA, DMT, and novel compounds.

