## FAQ

### How many psychedelic clinical trials are active globally?

More than 100 psychedelic clinical trials are reportedly active worldwide, although the exact number changes as studies begin, close, or stop recruiting.

### Which psychedelic is being studied the most?

Psilocybin is one of the most widely studied classic psychedelics. Researchers are investigating it for depression, anxiety, addiction, eating disorders, obsessive-compulsive disorder, and distress associated with serious illness.

### What is the most advanced psychedelic trial for addiction?

LSD research for alcohol use disorder is among the most advanced areas of modern psychedelic addiction research. Several other studies are also examining psilocybin and related therapies for substance use disorders.

### Is MDMA a psychedelic?

MDMA is often grouped with psychedelics, although it works differently from classic psychedelics such as psilocybin and LSD. It is commonly described as an empathogen or entactogen because of its effects on emotional openness, trust, and social connection.

### Are psychedelic clinical trials legal in Australia?

Yes. Approved universities, hospitals, clinics, and research organisations can legally conduct psychedelic clinical trials in Australia under strict regulatory and ethics requirements.

### Can I volunteer for a psychedelic clinical trial?

Possibly. Each study has specific eligibility criteria involving age, diagnosis, medications, physical health, mental health history, and location. Search an official clinical trial registry and contact the research team directly.

### Will psychedelic medicines be covered by insurance?

Coverage will depend on regulatory approval, the condition being treated, the treatment model, treatment costs, and the insurer. Wider coverage will require strong evidence of safety, effectiveness, and cost-effectiveness.

### When will psychedelic therapy become widely available?

There is no single timeline. Availability will depend on trial results, regulatory decisions, practitioner training, treatment costs, healthcare funding, and the development of safe clinical standards.

### Are positive clinical trial results enough for approval?

No. Regulators also assess study quality, safety data, manufacturing standards, practitioner requirements, treatment protocols, and whether the potential benefits outweigh the risks.

### What psychedelic clinical trials should people watch?

Major areas include psilocybin for treatment-resistant depression, MDMA-assisted therapy for PTSD, LSD for alcohol use disorder, short-acting DMT treatments, ketamine research, and psychedelic therapies for serious or neurodegenerative illness.

Psychedelic medicine is entering a more demanding phase. The field must now prove that encouraging results can be repeated, delivered safely, and translated into treatments that patients can realistically access.
